\section{Introduction}\label{sec:Introduction}
\noindent This section provides an overview of the company, followed by a presentation of the problem formulation and motivation for the study. It also includes a review of relevant literature.

\subsection{About Vermiculus}\label{sec: Vermiculus}
Vermiculus is a software company that provides modern, high-performance technology solutions for global capital markets, specifically targeting exchanges, clearing houses, and central securities depositories (CSDs)  \footnote{See \url{https://www.vermiculus.se/}. Last accessed 11.03.26.}. This thesis is performed in cooperation with Vermiculus, Stockholm, ensuring close alignment between academic research and real-world financial market applications.

\subsection{Problem description}
Vermiculus customers operate in financial markets characterized by both opportunities and inherent risks. In derivatives trading, one commonly used risk management strategy is hedging, where the objective is to reduce exposure to price fluctuations by dynamically trading the underlying asset over time.
\\\\
A central challenge in this context is the accurate pricing and hedging of financial derivatives, such as options. A widely used method for pricing European options is the Black–Scholes model, which relies on several simplifying assumptions, including continuous-time trading, frictionless markets, constant volatility, and the absence of transaction costs.
\\\\
However, these assumptions do not fully reflect real market conditions. To address these limitations, this thesis explores an alternative approach based on deep reinforcement learning, which has the potential to learn adaptive hedging strategies directly from interactions with the market environment.

\subsection{Aim of Thesis}
The aim of this thesis is to investigate the use of deep reinforcement learning for option hedging in non-perfect markets. The deep reinforcement approach will be compared to the classical Black-Scholes delta hedging approach, leading to the following research question:  
\\

\begin{compactenum}[{\bfseries RQ}1]
    \item \label{item:RQ1} Is it possible to outperform the Black-Scholes delta hedging approach with reinforcement learning?
    \item \label{item:RQ2} Can we create a multi-agent system that perform better than the agents separately?
    \item \label{item:RQ3} How is the agents performing if they have constraints?
\end{compactenum}
