\subsection{Literature review}
The main book used for reinforcement learning theory is the book \textit{Reinforcement Learning an introduction} by \cite{sutton2018reinforcement}. The method and application to hedging is related to the work of \cite{cao2020deephedging} in their article \textit{Deep Hedging of Derivatives Using Reinforcement Learning}.
\\\\
The theory of reinforcement learning dates back to the 1950´s. But the field did not gain significant attention until 2013, when DeepMind demonstrated that the system could learn to play arcade games created by Atari without any prior knowledge. The advances in computational power and the integration of deep neural networks have enabled reinforcement learning to solve complex high-dimensional problems, and it has been demonstrating success in many fields.

\subsection{Limitations}
The scope for this master thesis has been limited in several ways. First, only simulated data has been used. Second, the analysis is restricted to a single call option used for hedging purposes. Finally, the time horizon is fixed, with a predetermined number of trading days to maturity and exactly one re-hedging opportunity per day.
\\\\
Risks -  Training RL models is expensive, often requiring millions of interactions to learn effectively, which can be prohibitive for smaller projects.\\
 Agents often require massive amounts of data to learn, making them less suitable for scenarios where data is expensive to collect\\
 RL systems can be difficult to debug. Reward engineering—telling the AI what you want it to do—often involves a tedious, trial-and-error process.
