\section{Background}
This section first provides the necessary financial background, followed by an introduction to reinforcement learning and an explanation of why it is suitable for this thesis.

\subsection{Financial Background}\label{sec: Finance}
This section introduces the core financial concepts underlying the thesis, focusing on options and hedging.

\subsubsection{Options}
This thesis considers the hedging of a European call option. An option is a financial derivative that grant the right, but not the obligation, to either buy or sell an asset at a predetermined price (the strike price) on or before a specified date. Options may therefore be either call options or put options, and they are further classified according to the flexibility of their exercise date. One of the simplest variants is the European option, which can only be exercised at maturity. A call option generates profit if the price of the underlying asset rises above the strike price, while a put option becomes profitable if the price falls below the strike price (\cite{investments}, p.51-52). 
\\\\
It is also possible to write an option, meaning that an investor sells an option contract they do not own, thereby assuming the obligation to fulfill the contract terms should the buyer choose to exercise the option. In exchange for bearing this risk, the option writer receives a premium. These features give rise to four basic options positions: long call, short call, long put, and short put. 

\subsubsection{Black–Scholes Delta Hedging}
The Black–Scholes model provides a theoretical framework for pricing European options. The value of a call option depends on the underlying asset price, strike price, volatility, risk-free interest rate, and time to maturity. The price is given by (\cite{investments}, p.725, eq.21.1):
\begin{equation}
C_0 = S_0 N(d_1) - X e^{-rT} N(d_2)
\label{eq:bs_call}
\end{equation}

where
\begin{equation*}
d_1 = \frac{\ln(S_0 / X) + \left(r + \frac{\sigma^2}{2}\right)T}{\sigma \sqrt{T}},
\qquad
d_2 = d_1 - \sigma \sqrt{T}.
\end{equation*}

\begin{align*}
C_0 & = \text{current call option value}, \\
S_0 & = \text{current stock price}, \\
N(d) & = \text{cumulative distribution function of the standard normal distribution}, \\
X & = \text{exercise (strike) price}, \\
r & = \text{risk-free interest rate (continuously compounded)}, \\
T & = \text{time to expiration (in years)}, \\
\sigma & = \text{standard deviation of the stock's continuously compounded return}.
\end{align*}
In addition to providing a pricing formula, the Black–Scholes model also enables the construction of a hedging strategy. This is done using the option’s delta, which measures how sensitive the option price is to changes in the underlying asset price. More specifically, delta indicates how much the option value changes for a small change in the underlying price.
\\\\
Delta hedging involves taking a position in the underlying asset that offsets this sensitivity. For example, if the delta of a call option is 0.5, the hedging strategy consists of holding 0.5 units of the underlying asset per option contract. In this way, small changes in the asset price are approximately canceled out, reducing the overall risk of the position.
\\\\
Since the delta evolves over time as market conditions change, the hedge must be continuously rebalanced. Under the assumptions of the Black–Scholes model, such as continuous trading, absence of transaction costs, and constant volatility, this dynamic rebalancing results in a theoretically perfect hedge.
\\\\
In practice, however, these assumptions do not hold, which creates the need for another approach.

\subsection{Machine Learning}\label{sec: Machine Learning}
Over the past decade, machine learning has experienced rapid development, driven by advances in computational power, increased data availability, and progress in neural network architectures. These developments have enabled algorithms to solve increasingly complex problems in areas such as computer vision, natural language processing, and decision-making. One branch of machine learning that has received growing attention is reinforcement learning (RL), which focuses on learning optimal behaviour through interaction with an environment. Reinforcement learning is a subfield of machine learning concerned with sequential decision-making problems. In reinforcement learning, an agent interacts with an environment and learns a strategy, known as a policy, by receiving rewards based on the actions it takes (p.26 \cite{Hands_on_machine_learning_with_Scikit-Learn})

\subsection{Reinforcement learning}\label{sec: Reinforcement Learning}
Reinforcement learning addresses sequential decision-making problems where an agent interacts with an environment by taking actions and receiving feedback in the form of rewards. Through repeated interaction, the agent learns a strategy, known as a policy, that aims to maximize the cumulative reward over time. Unlike supervised learning, where models are trained on labeled datasets, reinforcement learning is based on trial-and-error exploration to discover effective strategies (p.2, \cite{sutton2018reinforcement}). This makes RL particularly suitable for problems where decisions must be made dynamically under uncertainty.\\
\\
Many real-world decision problems can be formulated as stochastic control problems, where an agent must determine optimal actions in an uncertain and evolving environment. Traditionally, such problems have been studied using tools from dynamic programming and stochastic calculus. However, these methods often rely on strong assumptions or become computationally infeasible when the environment is complex or high-dimensional. Reinforcement learning offers a flexible alternative by approximating optimal strategies directly through interaction with simulated environments.\\
\\
In recent years, reinforcement learning has demonstrated remarkable success in several domains. A well-known example is the work by DeepMind, where RL combined with deep neural networks enabled algorithms to outperform human experts in complex games such as Go and Atari video games. These successes have increased interest in applying reinforcement learning to other domains involving complex sequential decisions, including finance.


\subsection{Reinforcement learning in finance}\label{sec: Reinforcement learning in finance}
Financial markets present a natural setting for sequential decision-making under uncertainty. Tasks such as portfolio optimization, algorithmic trading, and risk management all involve making decisions over time based on evolving market conditions. One important problem in financial risk management is the hedging of derivative securities, such as options. Hedging strategies aim to reduce the financial risk associated with price movements in the underlying asset.

