\subsubsection{Elements of Reinforcement learning}\label{sec:Elements of reinforcement learning}
Reinforcement learning is a framework for modeling sequential decision-making problems.
The fundamentals of reinforcement learning involve an \textit{agent} that interacts with an \textit{environment} by making \textit{observations}, taking \textit{actions}, and receiving \textit{rewards}. This process can be seen in Figure \ref{fig:2.1Reinforcement learning}, and it will be explained more in detail later in the thesis.

\begin{figure} [h!]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.5\linewidth]{Template/Figures/2.1Reinforcement.png}
    \caption{The interaction between agent and environment, \cite{sutton2018reinforcement}, p.48}
    \label{fig:2.1Reinforcement learning}
\end{figure}
\noindent At each timestep t, the agent observes the current state, $S_t$, selects and action, $A_t$, and receives feedback in form of a reward, $R_t$. As a consequence of the action, $A_t$, the environment transitions to a new state, $S_{t+1}$. This interaction continues over over a sequence of time steps and the end of a time sequence form an episode. This interaction continues over multiple episodes and form the basis of the learning process. The environment will be explained more in detailed under Section \ref{sec: Enviroment}, and the agent will be explained more in Section \ref{sec:Agents}.
\\
\\
The objective of the agent is to learn a behavior, also known as a policy, that maximizes the cumulative reward over time. How the reward is defined and evaluated will be described in Section \ref{sec: Return and Value functions}, and how the policy is defined is described in Section \ref{sec: policy}


\subsubsection{Core components}\label{sec:Core components, 3.1}
Several key components define a reinforcement learning problem. 

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{State, ($S_t$):} A representation of the current situation of the environment.
    \item \textbf{Action, ($A_t$):} A decision taken by the agent that decide/influence the next state.
    \item \textbf{Reward, ($R_t$):} A numerical signal that evaluates the immediate outcome of an action.
    \item \textbf{Policy, ($\pi$):} A mapping from states to actions describing the behavior of the agent. The policy can be expressed as a probability distribution over actions given a state. 
\end{itemize}


\subsubsection{Policy}\label{sec: policy}
The policy is a central object in reinforcement learning, it determines how the agent behaves. During training, the agent seeks to improve its policy in order to maximize the expected return defined in Equation \ref{eq:Reward function}. 
The policy, denoted as $\pi$, defines how the agent behaves at a given state, in practice mapping states to actions. The policy is formally defined as the probability distribution over actions for every possible state (\cite{DeepRLHandsOn}, p.22): 
\begin{equation}\label{eq:policy}
    \pi(a|s)=P[A_t=a|S_t=s]
\end{equation}
where the expression describes the probability that the agent selects action $a$ when it is in state $s$.
\\\\
Policies can be deterministic or stochastic. A deterministic policy always selects the same action for a given state, meaning the action is directly determined by the state. In contrast, a stochastic policy assigns probabilities to different actions, allowing the agent to select among several possible actions according to a probability distribution (\cite{DeepRLHandsOn}, p.22).
\\\\
During training in reinforcement learning, the policy is continuously updated as the agent interacts with the environment. To learn an optimal policy, the agent must have a balance between exploration and exploitation (\cite{cao2020deephedging}, p.5). The agent ultimately searches for a policy that maximizes the expected value of rewards, as seen in Equation \ref{eq:Reward function} (\cite{kolm2019dynamicreplication}, p. 161).


\subsection{Markov Decision Process}\label{sec: Markov decision procecss}
\todo[]{How do we mathematically model the environment}
\noindent To be able to analyze reinforcement learning problems, a mathematical framework is required. This is provided to us by the Markov Decision Process (MDP), which models sequential decision making in environments with uncertain outcomes. In such environments, outcomes are partly controlled by a decision maker and partly determined by randomness. In reinforcement learning, MDPs form the theoretical foundation for representing the environment and defining the agent’s objective  \footnote{See \url{https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/computer-science/markov-decision-process}. Last accessed 12.03.26}.
\\\\
Within this framework, the agent acts as the decision maker and aims to learn a policy that maximizes the expected cumulative reward over time. One of the challenges in reinforcement learning is that an action influences not only the immediate reward. but also future outcomes, since the chosen action affects the state in which the agent will subsequently find itself. As a result, decision-making in MDPs involves a trade-off between immediate and delayed rewards (\cite{sutton2018reinforcement}, p.47).
\subsubsection{Tuple (S, A, P, R)}
In reinforcement learning, the agent interacts with an environment over a sequence of discrete time steps. At each time step $t$, the agent observes a state $S_t$, selects an action $A_t$, receives a reward $R_{t+1}$, and transitions to a new state $S_{t+1}$. This interaction generates a sequence known as a trajectory. Formally, a MDP is defined as a tuple:
\[
(S, A, P, R)
\]
where
\begin{itemize}
    \item $S$ is the set of states,
    \item $A$ is the set of actions,
    \item $P$ denotes the transition probabilities, and
    \item $R$ represents the reward function.
\end{itemize}
The dynamics of a Markov Decision Process (MDP) is described by the probability of transitioning to a new state and receiving a reward, given the current state and action (\cite{sutton2018reinforcement} p. 48, eq 3.2):
\begin{equation} \label{eq: MDP dynamics}
    p(s', r \mid s, a) = \Pr(S_t = s', R_t = r \mid S_{t-1} = s, A_{t-1} = a).
\end{equation}
From this function we can also define the state transition probability (\cite{sutton2018reinforcement} p. 49, eq 3.4):
\begin{equation}
    p(s' \mid s, a) = \Pr(S_t = s' \mid S_{t-1} = s, A_{t-1} = a),
\end{equation}
and the expected reward function (\cite{sutton2018reinforcement} p. 49, eq 3.5):
\begin{equation}
    r(s,a) = \mathbb{E}[R_t \mid S_{t-1} = s, A_{t-1} = a].
\end{equation}
In a finite MDP, the sets of state, actions and rewards, denoted by $\mathcal{S}$, $\mathcal{A}$ and $\mathcal{R}$, respectively contain a finite number of elements. The variables $R_t$ and $S_t$ are treated as random variables, and $s' \in \mathcal{S}$ denotes the next possible state. 

\subsubsection{Markov Property}
A key assumption underlying MDP's is the Markov property, which states that the future evaluation of the system depends only of the current state and action, not the past history (\cite{sutton2018reinforcement}, p.49). Formally, this implies that the conditional probability of the next state $S_{t+1}$ and reward, $R_{t+1}$, depends only on the present state, $S_t$, and action, $A_t$, as seen in Equation \ref{eq: MDP dynamics}. This assumption significantly simplifies the learning problem, as the agent does not need to consider the entire sequence of past events when making decisions.

\subsection{Return and Value functions} \label{sec: Return and Value functions}
\todo[]{How do we evaluate these decisions?}
In reinforcement learning, the objective of the agent is to maximize the cumulative reward over time. To evaluate how good a particular state or action is, value function are introduced. These functions quantify return and form the foundation of decision making in reinforcement learning. 

\subsubsection{Return and Reward Signal}\label{sec:Return and Reward Signal}
To be able to determine how well a policy operates, the agent will evaluate the reward signal.
The reward signal specifies the objective of the learning process by providing feedback on the agent’s actions. The reward is obtained periodically in the environment, where the agent receives a numerical value. The reward signal therefore indicates which outcomes are desirable or undesirable and guides the learning process. If an action results in a low or unfavorable reward, the policy may be updated so that the agent selects a different action in similar situations in the future (\cite{sutton2018reinforcement}, p. 6).
\\\\
In contrast, the value function evaluates the long-term desirability of states or actions by estimating the expected cumulative future reward (\cite{sutton2018reinforcement}, p. 6). The reward signal, defined as $R_{t+1}$, provides immediate feedback to the agent after taking an action. The overall objective is however not to maximize individual rewards, but the cumulative reward over time, this is referred to as the discounted sum of future rewards, $G_t$.
\\
\\
The return at time step $t$ is defined as:
\begin{equation}\label{eq:Reward function}
    G_t = R_{t+1} + \gamma R_{t+2} + \gamma^2 R_{t+3} + ... + \gamma^{T-1} R_{T} 
\end{equation}
where T is the terminal time and $\gamma\in(0,1]$ is a discount factor. The discount factor determines the relative importance of future rewards relative to immediate rewards (\cite{sutton2018reinforcement}, p.55, eq 3.8). A discount factor close to one places more weight on future rewards, while smaller value prioritizes short term gains. 

\subsubsection{State-Value function}\label{sec:State-Value function}
The framework for a Markov decision process is defined by the state-value function, $v_\pi(s)$, as the expected value when an agent is in state $s$ and follows the policy $\pi$. The value function is defined as 
 \begin{equation}
     v_\pi(s) = \mathbb{E}_\pi[G_t | S_t = s ]  \label{eq:value function 3.10}
 \end{equation}
where $G_t$ is the reward function, equation \ref{eq:Reward function}. 
 $ \mathbb{E}_\pi[.]$ denotes the expected return of a random variable given that the agent follow policy $\pi$, at any time step $t$ (\cite{sutton2018reinforcement}, p.70, eq.3.12).

\subsubsection{Action-Value function}\label{sec:Action-Value function}
While the state-value function evaluates states, the action-value function evaluates the state-action pairs. It is defined as the expected value if the agents takes an action, $a$, from state, $s$, and following the policy $\pi$. It is defined as 
\begin{equation}
    q_\pi(s,a) = \mathbb{E}_\pi[G_t | S_t = s, A_t = a]  
    \label{eq: action-value function 3.11}
\end{equation}
where $G_t$ is the reward function, \ref{eq:Reward function}. $ \mathbb{E}_\pi[.]$ denotes the expected return of a random variable given that the agent follow policy $\pi$, at any time step $t$ (\cite{sutton2018reinforcement}, p.70, eq.3.13)
The action-value function is often refer to as the q-value. 

\subsubsection{Connection between the Value functions}
The state and action value are closely related, the value of a state can be expressed as the expected value on the action-value function under the given policy: 
\begin{equation}\label{eq: value function conditional on space,action}
    v_\pi(s) = \sum \pi(a|s)q_\pi(s,a).
\end{equation}
Hence, the value function can be expressed as the return conditional of the current space, action, weighted by the probability of taking each action (law of total probability) .

\subsubsection{Transition to Bellman equation}
Although value function provide a way to evaluate states and action, computing them directly is often infeasible, especially in complex environments. Instead, value function can be expressed recursive in complex environments using the Bellman equation which forms the basis for many reinforcement learning algorithms. This is introduced in the next Section.


\subsection{The Bellman equation}\label{sec:Bellman equation}
\todo[]{Why RL is solvable recursively}
The Bellman equation provides a recursive relationship for value functions and is central to reinforcement learning. It expresses the value of a state as the expected immediate reward plus the discounted value of subsequent states. It allows us to convert information of the environment into improvements of the agents behavior. The value function can be expressed recursively, and the Bellman equation breaks down the state in the initial reward plus the discounted value of the later rewards.
\\
\\
To derive the Bellman equation, we begin with the definition of the return from Equation \ref{eq:Reward function}:
\begin{equation}
    G_t = R_{t+1} + \gamma R_{t+2} + \gamma^2 R_{t+3} + \dots
\end{equation}
This expression can be rewritten recursively as
\begin{equation}
\label{eq: recursive return}
    G_t = R_{t+1} + \gamma G_{t+1}
\end{equation}
and using the definition of the state-value function,
\begin{equation}
    v_\pi(s) = \mathbb{E}_\pi[G_t \mid S_t = s],
\end{equation}
we can condition on the first action taken:
\begin{equation}
    v_\pi(s) = \sum_a \pi(a \mid s) \mathbb{E}_\pi[G_t \mid S_t = s, A_t = a].
\end{equation}
Substituting the recursive expression for the return from Equation \ref{eq: recursive return}, we obtain:
\begin{equation}
    \mathbb{E}_\pi[G_t \mid S_t = s, A_t = a]
    = \mathbb{E}_\pi[ R_{t+1} + \gamma G_{t+1} \mid S_t = s, A_t = a].
\end{equation}
By linearity of expectation, this can be written as:
\begin{equation}
    = \mathbb{E}_\pi[ R_{t+1} \mid S_t = s, A_t = a]
    + \gamma \mathbb{E}_\pi[ G_{t+1} \mid S_t = s, A_t = a].
\end{equation}

The first term corresponds to the expected immediate reward, while the second term represents the expected future return. Using the Markov property, the future return depends only on the next state \( S_{t+1} \), which allows us to write:
\begin{equation}
    \mathbb{E}_\pi[ G_{t+1} \mid S_t = s, A_t = a]
    = \mathbb{E}_\pi[ v_\pi(S_{t+1}) \mid S_t = s, A_t = a].
\end{equation}

Substituting this back, we obtain:
\begin{equation}
    \mathbb{E}_\pi[G_t \mid S_t = s, A_t = a]
    = \mathbb{E}_\pi[ R_{t+1} + \gamma v_\pi(S_{t+1}) \mid S_t = s, A_t = a].
\end{equation}

Finally, by incorporating the transition probabilities of the MDP, the Bellman equation for the state-value function becomes:
\begin{equation}
\label{eq: Bellman-equation value function}
    v_\pi(s) = \sum_a \pi(a \mid s) \sum_{s',r} p(s', r \mid s, a) \left[ r + \gamma v_\pi(s') \right].
\end{equation}

The Bellman equation shows that the value of a state is equal to the expected return obtained by taking an action according to the policy and then following the same policy thereafter. This recursive structure forms the foundation for many reinforcement learning algorithms.



\subsection{Bellman optimality}\label{sec: Bellman optimality}
\todo[]{How do we compute/approximate the value function}
The goal in reinforcement learning is to find a policy that maximizes the expected cumulative reward. For a finite Markov Decision Process, there exists at least one optimal policy, denoted by \( \pi_* \), which achieves the highest value for all states.
\\\\
The optimal state-value function is defined as:
\begin{equation}
    v_*(s) = \max_\pi v_\pi(s), \quad \forall s \in \mathcal{S},
\end{equation}
and represents the maximum expected return achievable from state \( s \) (\cite{sutton2018reinforcement}, p.63, eq.3.15).
\\\\
Similarly, the optimal action-value function is defined as:
\begin{equation}
    q_*(s,a) = \max_\pi q_\pi(s,a), \quad \forall s \in \mathcal{S}, \, a \in \mathcal{A}.
\end{equation}
The optimal value functions satisfy the Bellman optimality equations (\cite{sutton2018reinforcement}, p.62, eq.3.16). For the state-value function, this can be written as:
\begin{equation}
\label{eq: bellman optimality v}
    v_*(s) = \max_a \sum_{s',r} p(s', r \mid s, a) \left[ r + \gamma v_*(s') \right].
\end{equation}
This equation shows that the value of a state is equal to the maximum expected return obtainable by choosing the best possible action and thereafter acting optimally (\cite{sutton2018reinforcement}, p.~63, eq.3.19).
\\
\\
The corresponding Bellman optimality equation for the action-value function is given by:
\begin{equation}
\label{eq: bellman optimality q}
    q_*(s,a) = \sum_{s',r} p(s', r \mid s, a) \left[ r + \gamma \max_{a'} q_*(s',a') \right].
\end{equation}
This formulation expresses the value of taking action \( a \) in state \( s \), followed by optimal actions in subsequent states (\cite{sutton2018reinforcement}, p.~64, eq.3.20).
\\
\subsubsection{Transition to approximating Bellman optimality}
The Bellman optimality equations are fundamental, as they provide a recursive characterization of the optimal value functions. Many reinforcement learning algorithms aim to approximate or solve these equations in order to identify optimal policies.
\\
\\
The Bellman optimality equations provide a powerful characterization of the optimal value functions. In principle, solving these equations yields the optimal policy for a given reinforcement learning problem. 
\\\\
However, obtaining an exact solution typically relies on several strong assumptions. First, the transition dynamics of the environment must be known. Second, the state and action spaces must be sufficiently small to allow for tractable computation. Third, the problem must satisfy the Markov property. 
\\\\
In practice, these assumptions are rarely fully satisfied, especially in complex or high-dimensional environments. As a result, it is generally not feasible to solve the Bellman optimality equations exactly. Instead, various approximation methods are employed to estimate value functions and derive near-optimal policies (\cite{sutton2018reinforcement}, p.~66).

\subsection{Estimation of the Bellman equations}
\todo[]{How do we compute/approximate the value function}
Several approaches have been developed to approximate the value functions implied by the Bellman equations. In the following Sections, Dynamic Programming, Monte Carlo methods, Temporal Difference learning, and Q-learning are introduced. These methods represent different techniques for estimating Bellman and form the basis for many reinforcement learning algorithms.
\subsubsection{Dynamic Programming}

Dynamic Programming (DP) refers to a set of methods used to find optimal policies which have complete knowledge of the environment, as an MDP. In other words, DP is used to solve reinforcement learning problems when a complete model of the environment is available. In particular, DP assumes that the transition probabilities \( p(s',r \mid s,a) \) and the reward function (equation \ref{eq: expected reward function}) are known. Under these assumptions, the Bellman equations can be solved exactly.
\\\\
Two central components of dynamic programming are \textbf{policy evaluation} and \textbf{policy improvement}. Policy evaluation consists of computing the state-value function \( v_\pi(s) \) for a given policy \( \pi \), typically by iteratively applying the Bellman expectation equation until convergence (\cite{sutton2018reinforcement}, p.~74). Policy improvement, on the other hand, updates the policy by selecting actions that maximize the expected return based on the current value function (\cite{sutton2018reinforcement}, p.~80).
\\\\
By alternating between policy evaluation and policy improvement, the policy can be iteratively refined. This process is known as \textbf{policy iteration} and is guaranteed to converge to an optimal policy in finite Markov Decision Processes
\begin{equation}
    \pi_0 \xrightarrow{\mathbb{E}} v_{\pi_0} \xrightarrow{I} \pi_1 \xrightarrow{\mathbb{E}} v_{\pi_1} \xrightarrow{I} \pi_2
 \xrightarrow{\mathbb{E}}\dots \xrightarrow{I} \pi_* \xrightarrow{\mathbb{E}} v_{\pi_*}.
 \end{equation}
Where $ \xrightarrow{\mathbb{E}}$ denotes the policy evaluation and $ \xrightarrow{\mathbb{I}}$ denotes the policy improvement (\cite{sutton2018reinforcement}, p.96).
\\\\
An alternative approach in DP is \textbf{value iteration}, which directly applies the Bellman optimality equation to update the value function. Instead of evaluating a fixed policy, value iteration combines evaluation and improvement into a single update step:
\begin{equation}
    v_{k+1}(s) = \max_a \sum_{s',r} p(s',r \mid s,a)\left[r + \gamma v_k(s')\right].
\end{equation}
(\cite{sutton2018reinforcement}, p.~100, eq.~4.10).
While dynamic programming provides a theoretically sound framework for solving reinforcement learning problems, it is rarely applicable in practice. The requirement of a known environment model and the need to perform updates over the entire state space make DP infeasible for large or complex problems.
\\\\
These limitations motivate the development of model-free methods, which can learn directly from experience without requiring knowledge of the environment dynamics. Such approaches are introduced in the following Sections.
\newpage
\subsubsection{Monte Carlo Methods}
Monte Carlo (MC) methods address some of the key limitations of dynamic programming by removing the requirement of a known environment model. In many real-world problems, the model would need to perform updates on the entire state space, making it unachievable in large, and complex problems.  Instead of relying on transition probabilities, MC methods learn value functions directly from sampled experience (\cite{sutton2018reinforcement}, p.~91).
\\\\
In MC methods, value estimates are based on complete episodes of interaction with the environment. After an episode has terminated, the return \( G_t \) can be computed for each visited state, and the value function is updated as an average of the observed returns. In this way, MC methods learn directly from trajectories generated by following a policy. This approach makes MC methods model-free, as they do not require knowledge of the transition dynamics \( p(s',r \mid s,a) \). Instead, they rely solely on observed trajectories generated by following a policy.\\
\begin{wrapfigure}{r}{0.35\textwidth}
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=1\linewidth]{Template/Figures/Figures Theory/monte carlo.png}
    \caption{One Monte Carlo episode, visualizing how returns are assigned to visited states after an episode has terminated.}
    \label{fig:Monte Carlo iteration}
\end{wrapfigure}
A common approach is the every-visit Monte Carlo method, where the value function is updated as:
\begin{equation}
    V(S_t) \leftarrow V(S_t) + \alpha \left[ G_t - V(S_t) \right],
\end{equation}
where \( \alpha \) is a constant step-size parameter (\cite{sutton2018reinforcement}, eq.~6.1, p.~144).
\\\\
The key characteristic of Monte Carlo methods is that updates can only be performed after an episode has ended, since the return requires knowledge of all future rewards within that episode (\cite{cao2020deephedging}, p.~7). This is visualized in Figure \ref{fig:Monte Carlo iteration}. This can lead to high variance in the estimates, especially in problems with long episodes, as the return depends on the entire sequence of rewards.
Despite this, MC methods have the advantage of producing unbiased estimates of the value function, since they use actual observed returns rather than bootstrapped estimates.
\\\\
In summary, Monte Carlo methods provide a conceptually simple approach to learning value functions from experience. However, their reliance on complete episodes and the resulting high variance motivate the development of more efficient methods. This leads to Temporal Difference learning, which combines ideas from both dynamic programming and Monte Carlo methods.
\newpage
\subsubsection{Temporal Difference Learning}
\begin{wrapfigure}{r,b}{0.35\textwidth}
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=1\linewidth]{Template/Figures/Figures Theory/1 step TD.png}
    \caption{TD iteration}
    \label{fig:1 step TD}
\end{wrapfigure}
Temporal Difference (TD) learning combines key ideas from both dynamic programming and Monte Carlo methods. Like Monte Carlo methods, TD learning is model-free and learns directly from experience. At the same time, it incorporates the recursive structure of the Bellman equation, similar to dynamic programming, (\cite{sutton2018reinforcement}, p.~74).
However, TD learning does not need to wait until the end of an episode to update its estimates like Monte Carlo (\cite{sutton2018reinforcement}, p.~119). Instead, TD methods can learn after a defined time step. TD is similar to dynamic programming, where value functions are updated using other value estimates derived from the Bellman equation 
\\\\
The main idea of TD learning is to update value estimates based on other learned estimates, rather than waiting for the final outcome of an episode like Monte Carlo, visualized in figure \ref{fig:1 step TD}. This is known as \textit{bootstrapping} (\cite{sutton2018reinforcement}, p.~119).
\\\\
Instead of using the full return \( G_t \), TD methods use a one-step estimate of the return (\cite{sutton2018reinforcement}, p.~144):
\begin{equation}
    R_{t+1} + \gamma v_\pi(S_{t+1}).
\end{equation}
This leads to TD(0), or \textit{one-step} TD, which is the simplest TD-method. The update rule for the state-value function is defined as:
\begin{equation}
    v_\pi(S_t) \leftarrow v_\pi(S_t) + \alpha \left[\underbrace{ R_{t+1} + \gamma v_\pi(S_{t+1})}_{\textit{estimate of the return}} - v_\pi(S_t) \right],
\end{equation}
where \( \alpha \in (0,1] \) is the learning rate (\cite{sutton2018reinforcement}, eq 6.1, p.~144).
\\\\
The term in brackets,
\begin{equation}
    \delta_t = R_{t+1} + \gamma v_\pi(S_{t+1}) - v_\pi(S_t),
\end{equation}
is referred to as the \textit{temporal difference error} (\cite{sutton2018reinforcement}, eq. 7.10, p.178). It represents the difference between the predicted value and a one-step improved estimate.
\\\\
Compared to Monte Carlo methods, TD learning has lower variance, since it does not rely on full episode returns. However, this comes at the cost of introducing some bias, as the updates depend on current value estimates. In summary, TD learning provides a more efficient and practical approach to estimating value functions, particularly in problems with long or continuing tasks. This framework forms the basis for many modern reinforcement learning algorithms, including Q-learning, which is introduced in the next Section.

\subsubsection{Q-learning}\label{sec:Q-learning}
\todo[]{Bellman in action}
Q-learning is a model-free reinforcement learning algorithm used to learn the optimal action-value function. Unlike previous methods, which focus on evaluating a given policy, Q-learning directly aims to approximate the optimal policy by learning the optimal action-value function \( q_*(s,a) \). Q-leaning is off-policy, which is explained further down in the Section. By using the Bellman equation the Q-values\footnote{Also known as action-values \ref{sec:Action-Value function}} are updated iteratively \footnote{See \url{https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/computer-science/deep-q-network}. Last accessed 01.04.26.}.
\\
\\
The method is based on the Bellman optimality equation for the action-value function:
\begin{equation}
    q_*(s,a) = \mathbb{E}\left[ R_{t+1} + \gamma \max_{a'} q_*(S_{t+1},a') \mid S_t = s, A_t = a \right].
\end{equation}
Q-learning approximates this relationship using sampled experience. At each time step, the action-value function is updated according to:
\begin{equation}
    Q(S_t, A_t) \leftarrow Q(S_t, A_t) + \alpha \left[ R_{t+1} + \gamma \max_{a'} Q(S_{t+1}, a) - Q(S_t, A_t) \right],
\end{equation}
where \( \alpha \in (0,1] \) is the learning rate (\cite{sutton2018reinforcement}, eq.6.6, p.~157).
\\\\
The term
\begin{equation}
    R_{t+1} + \gamma \max_{a'} Q(S_{t+1}, a')
\end{equation}
is referred to as the target, and represents a one-step approximation of the optimal return. The difference between this target and the current estimate defines the temporal difference error explained in the previous Section.
\\\\
The Q-learning algorithm uses a \textit{Q-table} to store and update the Q-values for the state-action pairs.
