A key feature of Q-learning is that it is an off-policy method. This means that the agent can learn the optimal policy independently of the policy used to generate data. In practice, this is often implemented using an exploratory behavior policy, such as an \(\epsilon\)-greedy strategy, while still updating towards the optimal policy.
\\\\
Compared to previous methods, Q-learning combines the advantages of Temporal Difference learning with the Bellman optimality principle, allowing it to learn optimal behavior directly from experience. This makes it a fundamental algorithm in reinforcement learning and forms the basis for many reinforcement learning agents. 
