\section{Method}\label{sec: Method}
This Section presents the methodology used in this study. It describes how the environment and the agent are implemented, as well as how the training and evaluation procedures are conducted. The overall objective is to learn an optimal hedging strategy for a European call option. The set-up for the implementation has been made following the example of \cite{MathWorksHedgingRL}, "Hedge Options Using Reinforcement Learning Toolbox".

\subsection{Environment}\label{sec: Enviroment}
The first step in the implementation is to define the environment in which the agent operates. After this we explain how the environment evolves from the current state to the next. 

\subsubsection{Environment Definition}
As illustrated in Figure \ref{fig:2.1Reinforcement learning}, the input to the environment is an action $A_t$, while the output is a state $S_{t+1}$ and a reward $R_{t+1}$. These components are defined as follows:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Action}: The action represents the hedging decision and corresponds to a continuous value between 0 and 1, indicating the proportion of the underlying asset held.
    \item \textbf{State}: The state consists of three variables observed by the agent: moneyness (defined as the ratio of the spot price to the strike price), time to maturity, and the current position in the underlying asset.
    \item \textbf{Reward}: The reward is defined using an accounting profit and loss (P\&L) formulation. At each time step, it is given by the change in portfolio value, adjusted for gains from the hedging position and transaction costs (\cite{cao2020deephedging}, p.11): 
    \begin{equation}
        R_{i+1} = V_{i+1} - V_i + H_i (S_{i+1} - S_i) - \kappa \lvert S_i (H_{i+1} - H_i) \rvert,
    \qquad 0 \le i < n,
    \end{equation}
    where \(S_i\) denotes the asset price at the beginning of period \(i\), and \(H_i\) represents the position held in the underlying asset over the interval \([i\Delta t, (i+1)\Delta t]\). The parameter \(\kappa\) captures proportional transaction costs, while \(V_i\) is the value of the derivative position at time \(i\). In addition to the stepwise rewards, transaction costs are also incurred when initiating and closing the hedge. The initial cost of establishing the position is given by $-\kappa \lvert S_0 H_0 \rvert$, and a corresponding cost is applied when the position is liquidated at the final time step: $-\kappa \lvert S_n H_n \rvert$ (\cite{cao2020deephedging}, p.11-12).
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection{Environment Evolution}
Now that all variables have been defined, the next step is to describe how the environment evolves at each time step. Given the current state $S_t$ and an action $A_t$, the environment transitions to a new state $S_{t+1}$ and produces a reward $R_{t+1}$.
\\\\
The underlying asset price follows a stochastic process modeled as Geometric Brownian Motion (\cite{cao2020deephedging}, p.14):
\begin{equation}
    dS = \mu S \, dt + \sigma S \, dz.
\end{equation}
In discrete time, this implies that the next asset price is generated using the current price, drift, volatility, and a Gaussian noise term. Simultaneously, the time to maturity decreases by a fixed increment $\Delta t$, and the episode terminates when the maturity approaches zero.
\\\\
The reward is computed based on the accounting profit and loss formulation described in the previous Section. The change in the value of the derivative is calculated using the Black-Scholes formula. To account for risk preferences, a quadratic penalty term is applied to the profit and loss, resulting in the final reward: $R_t = \mathrm{P\&L} - c \cdot (\mathrm{P\&L})^2$, where $c$ is a risk-aversion parameter that penalizes large fluctuations in returns (\cite{MathWorksHedgingRL}).
\\\\
Finally, the environment updates its internal state by setting the new asset price, time to maturity, and position equal to the chosen action. The updated state, the computed reward, and a termination signal are then returned to the agent.

\subsection{Agents}\label{sec:Agents}
After the environment is defined, we now turn to the decision-making component of the system, the agent. In the context of option hedging, the agent functions as a portfolio manager. Its objective is to make sequential decisions regarding the underlying asset to minimize risk. To address the complexities of non-perfect markets, we explore three different agents, which have been implemented using deep reinforcement learning. In the Section \ref{sec: theory}, the fundamentals to reinforcement was introduced, but as we have extended our work to deep reinforcement learning, some new concepts will be discussed. 

\subsubsection*{Shared Structure among the Agents}
All three agents share several key characteristics. The agents we have used are designed to handle high-dimensional state spaces through function approximation, which means a parameterized function is employed to represent the value function:
\begin{equation}
     \quad q_\pi(s,a) \approx q(s,a; \theta),
\end{equation}
where \( \theta \) denotes a set of parameters.
\\\\
The parameters are updated by minimizing the difference between predicted values and target values derived from the Bellman equation. This can be formulated as minimizing the squared temporal difference error:
\begin{equation}
\label{eq: Squared temporal difference error}
    \mathcal{L}(\theta) = \mathbb{E} \left[ \left( \underbrace{q(S_t, A_t; \theta)}_{\text{Predicted value}} - \underbrace{(R_{t+1} + \gamma \max_{a'} q(S_{t+1}, a'; \theta))}_{\text{Target value}} \right)^2 \right].
\end{equation}
The function approximator we have used is a neural network, which is what gives rise to deep reinforcement learning. Neural networks are capable of approximating complex, high-dimensional functions, making them suitable for problems where traditional tabular methods fail.
\\\\
Another shared feature among our three agents is that they are off-policy, meaning that the agent learns one policy, referred to as the target policy, while following a different policy, known as the behavior policy, to generate data. This separation makes the methods more powerful and general, as it offers a flexibility when dealing with the trade-off between exploration and exploitation. The downside when using off-policy methods are that they are often of greater variance and are slower to converge (\cite{sutton2018reinforcement}, p. 103, p.284). 
\\\\\
The agents also relays on temporal difference learning, meaning they build on bootstrapping. When combining function approximation, off-policy learning and bootstrapping, reinforcement learning algorithms may suffer from instability and even divergence. \cite{sutton2018reinforcement}, refer to this issue as the deadly triad. To mitigate the instability caused by the deadly triad, it is possible to employ techniques such as replay buffers and target networks.
\\\\
A replay buffer is a technique in which the agent’s experiences, consisting of state, action, reward, and next state tuples, are stored at each time step in a memory buffer. These stored transitions are later sampled to perform updates to the network parameters (\cite{MnihVolodymyr2013PAwD}, p.4). This approach improves data efficiency by allowing the agent to reuse past experiences multiple times. In addition, random sampling from the buffer breaks the correlations between the samples, which reduces the variance of the updates (\cite{MnihVolodymyr2013PAwD}, p.4-5).
\\\\
Target networks are used to further improve stability. Instead of using the same neural network to compute both the predicted value and the target value, in Equation \ref{eq: Squared temporal difference error}, a separate network, referred to as the target network, is maintained as a delayed copy of the main network  (\cite{DDPG}, p.4).
\\\\
An overview of the shared characteristics has now been given, but in the following three subsections a more detailed description of the three agents, called deep Q-network, deep deterministic policy gradient and twin delayed deep deterministic policy gradient, will be given. The difference between the three agents lies mainly in their way of handling action space and how they address stability and bias.  

\subsubsection{Deep Q-Network (DQN)}
The Deep Q-Network (DQN) algorithm is used for discrete action space and for us the actions are in the range $\in [0, 0.1, \dots, 0.9, 1]$. Deep Q-Networks combine classic Q-learning \ref{sec:Q-learning} with neural networks to approximate the Q-function. The Q-function as we have mentioned earlier is denoted as $Q(S_t, A_t, \theta)$ where $\theta$ is the neural network parameters. This allows the agent to learn in an efficient way when we have continuous or large state space. DQN therefore works in complex environment, where the tabular methods fails. 
\\\\
The goal when training the DQN is to minimize the error between the estimated $Q(S_t, A_t, \theta)$ and the true Q-function $Q(S_t, A_t)$. Since the true Q-function is unknown, we instead adjust the network parameters to minimize the error between the current estimate and a target value. This target represents what the Q-value would be by using Q-learning. The target is hence given by \footnote{See \url{https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/computer-science/deep-q-network}. Last accessed 01.04.26.}:
\begin{equation}
    y = r + \gamma \max_{a'} Q(s', a'; \theta_{targ}),
\end{equation}
where $\theta_{targ}$ is the parameters of the target network. To train the network, we minimize a loss function defined as the mean squared error between the predicted Q-value and the target value, as shown in Equation \ref{eq: Squared temporal difference error}. Importantly, the target network parameters are used in the computation of the target to improve training stability. The loss is minimized using the Adam optimizer, a gradient-based optimization method. Gradients of the loss with respect to the network parameters are computed via backpropagation and used to iteratively update the model weights.
\\\\
The DQN algorithm is an off-policy method, which allows it to balance exploration and exploitation during training. In this setting, exploration is handled using an epsilon greedy policy, denoted as $\pi_\epsilon$. This means that the agent follows a greedy policy with a probability of $1-\epsilon$ and a random policy with probability  $\epsilon$ (\cite{cao2020deephedging}, p.9): 
\[
\pi_{\epsilon}(S_t) =
\begin{cases}
\arg\max_{a \in A} Q(S_t, a), & \text{with probability } 1 - \epsilon, \\
\text{random } a \in A, & \text{with probability } \epsilon.
\end{cases}
\]
In the beginning of the training our $\epsilon$ is set to 1, meaning the agent is very exploratory. As the training continuous the epsilon is decreased, leading the agent to rely more on the learned policy. In the end of the learning procedure the greedy policy is always followed, and at last we get our optimal policy. 

\subsubsection{Deep Deterministic Policy Gradient (DDPG)}
The deep deterministic policy gradient (DDPG) algorithm can be used for continuous action space, unlike the DQN algorithm. The structure for the DDPG algorithm is seen in Figure \ref{fig:ActorCritic}, where it builds on an actor–critic architecture and Q-learning (\cite{DDPG}, p.2).

\begin{figure} [h!]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.8\linewidth]{ActorCritic.png}
    \caption{DDPG algorithm structure (\cite{DDPG}, p.3)}
    \label{fig:ActorCritic}
\end{figure}
The actor and critic are two neural networks, with the following tasks: 
\begin{itemize}
    \item The actor, represents the policy and determines which action to take given a state.
    \item The critic, estimates the Q-value function and evaluates how good a chosen action is.
\end{itemize}
This structure enables DDPG to combine policy learning with value estimation. In the next two parts, the critic and then actor network are explained in more detail. 

\subsubsection*{Critic Network}
The critic network takes in the current state and action as input and then outputs the corresponding Q-value (\cite{DDPG}, p.4). In this thesis the neural network for the critic was built using three fully connected layers and Rectified Linear Unit (ReLu) as activation functions. 
\\\\
The critic network is updated by minimizing the difference between the current predicted Q-value from the critic and a target value, which is constructed using the Bellman equation. The loss function that we want to minimize is hence given by (\cite{DDPG}, p.4, eq.7):
\begin{equation}
    \label{eq: critic loss function}
    L(\phi, \mathcal{D}) = \mathbb{E}_{(s,a,r,s', d) \sim \mathcal{D}} \left[ \left(  \underbrace{Q_\phi(s, a)}_{\text{Current Q-value}} -  \underbrace{(r + \gamma (1-d) Q_{\phi_{targ}}(s', \mu_{\theta_{targ}} (s')))}_{\text{Target value}} \right)^2 \right].
\end{equation}
where $Q_{\phi}$ denotes the critic neural network with parameters $\phi$. The parameters $\phi_{\text{targ}}$ correspond to a separate target network, which is updated according to (\cite{DDPG}, p.4, eq.6):
\begin{equation}
    \phi_{targ} = p\phi_{targ} + (1-p)\phi
    \label{eq: target networks}
\end{equation}
where $p \in[0,1]$ is a hyperparameter, often referred to as the Polyak coefficient. The target network is updated using soft updates, meaning that its parameters are slowly adjusted towards the parameters of the main network at each iteration. The term $d$ in the loss function indicates whether the next state is terminal, 1 if episode is done otherwise 0. The term $\mu_{\theta_{\text{targ}}}$ represents the target policy and $\mathcal{D} = (s,a,r,s', d)$ is a sampled set of transitions from the replay buffer. Equation \ref{eq: critic loss function} is minimized using the Adam optimizer, a gradient based optimization method.   

\subsubsection*{Actor Network}
The actor network takes in the current state and outputs an action. The neural network for the actor was built using three fully connected layers. ReLU activation functions are used in the hidden layers, while a sigmoid activation function is applied in the output layer to ensure that the action remains within the desired range 0 to 1.
\\\\
The actor is updated using policy gradients, which optimize the parameters of a policy by following the gradient in the direction of higher expected rewards. More specifically, it is trained to maximize the expected Q-value predicted by the critic (\cite{DDPG}, p.4, eq.8):
\begin{equation}
    \max_{\theta} \mathbb{E}{s \sim \mathcal{D}} \left[ Q{\phi}\big(s, \mu_{\theta}(s)\big) \right].
    \label{eq: critic ddpg}
\end{equation}
This means that for each state, the actor selects an action according to its policy, which is then evaluated by the critic. The actor’s parameters are updated to increase the expected Q-value, meaning it learns to choose actions that the critic predicts will lead higher long-term rewards. In practice, this optimization is implemented using gradient ascent. Since standard optimizers perform gradient descent, the objective was rewritten as the minimization of the negative Q-value. *Policy gradient methods learns the optimal policy directly. The agent improves its behavior by interacting with the environment and updating these parameters in the direction of higher action values (\cite{cao2020deephedging}, p.6). 
\\\\
Through the interaction between the two networks, the critic provides feedback that guides the actor toward improved decisions over time. The actor and critic are trained iteratively until convergence (\cite{cao2020deephedging}, p.11).

\subsubsection*{Exploration vs Exploitation}
The policy in DDPG is deterministic, meaning that a specific action is selected for each given state. While this allows for stable policy learning, it also limits exploration, as the agent will repeatedly choose the same action for the same state. To address this, noise is added to the action during training which encourage exploration. Several noise processes can be used for this purpose, and in this thesis, the Ornstein-Uhlenbeck (OU) process is applied (\cite{DeepRLHandsOn}, p.412).
\\\\
The OU process is stochastic and in a discrete-time setting, the process can be described as:
\begin{equation}
    x_{t+1} = x_t + \theta (\mu - x_t) + \sigma N,
\end{equation}
where $\theta$ determines the rate of mean reversion, $\mu$ is the long-term mean, $\sigma$ controls the magnitude of the noise, and N is normal noise. In this process the generated noise depends on its previous value, which creates a smoother and more consistent exploration pattern compared to independent random noise (\cite{DeepRLHandsOn}, p.412).
\\\\
