\subsubsection{Twin Delayed Deep Deterministic Policy Gradient (TD3)}
The Twin Delayed Deep Deterministic Policy Gradient (TD3) algorithm builds upon the actor–critic framework used in DDPG but introduces several modifications to address known issues such as overestimation bias and training instability. In particular, TD3 incorporates three key improvements: clipped double Q-learning, target policy smoothing, and delayed policy updates \footnote{See: \url{https://medium.com/@joanna.z.gryczka/td3-tutorial-and-implementation-682f16b56699}. Last accessed 16.03.26.}. The information about the TD3 algorithm is based on \cite{fujimoto2018td3} and OpenAI Spinning Up documentation about Twin Delayed DDPG \footnote{See:\url{https://spinningup.openai.com/en/latest/algorithms/td3.html#references}. Last accessed 19.03.26}.

\subsubsection*{Clipped double Q-learning}
Clipped double Q-learning in TD3 involves learning two separate Q-functions, denoted  $Q_{\phi_1}$ and $Q_{\phi_2}$. Instead of relying on a single estimate, the minimum of the two Q-values is used when constructing the target in the loss function. The target value from Equation \ref{eq: critic loss function} is hence changed to:
\begin{equation}
\label{eq: target value in TD3}
    y(r,s',d) = r + \gamma (1 - d) \min_{i=1,2} Q_{\phi_i,\text{targ}}\big(s', a'(s')\big).
\end{equation}
By using the smaller of the two estimates, the method produces more conservative targets, which helps against overestimation. Each Q-function is then trained independently by minimizing the mean squared error with respect to this shared target:
\begin{equation}
    L(\phi_1, \mathcal{D}) = \mathbb{E} \left[ \left( Q_{\phi_1}(s,a) - y(r,s',d) \right)^2 \right],
\end{equation}
\begin{equation}
    L(\phi_2, \mathcal{D}) = \mathbb{E} \left[ \left( Q_{\phi_2}(s,a) - y(r,s',d) \right)^2 \right].
\end{equation}
The policy is updated by maximizing the Q-value estimated by one of the critics, where we have used $Q_{\phi_1}$:
\begin{equation}
    \max_{\theta} \mathbb{E_{\text{s} \sim \mathcal{D}}} \left[ Q_{\phi_1}\big(s, \mu_{\theta}(s)\big) \right].
    \label{eq: critic ddpg}
\end{equation}

\subsubsection*{Target Policy Smoothing}
In addition to clipped double Q-learning, TD3 applies target policy smoothing by adding small noise to the target action, denoted as $a'(s')$, when computing the target value, see Equation \ref{eq: target value in TD3}. This noise is distinct from the exploration noise used in DDPG, which is added to the actor’s output during training, where we have used the OU process noise. In TD3, both types of noise are used, as they serve different purposes.
\\\\
The target policy smoothing noise is introduced to prevent the policy from exploiting sharp errors in the critic and encourages smoother value estimates. After adding the noise, the resulting action is clipped to ensure it remains within the valid action range, [0,1]. The target action is defined as:
\begin{equation}
    a'(s') = \text{clip}\left(\mu_{\theta_{\text{targ}}}(s') + \text{clip}(\epsilon,-c,c), a_{Low}, a_{High}\right), \;\;\;\;\; \epsilon \sim \mathcal{N}(0, \sigma)
\end{equation}
where the parameter c controls the maximum magnitude of the smoothing noise. 

\subsubsection*{Delayed Policy Updates}
The third improvement in TD3 is the use of delayed policy updates. In the DDPG algorithm, the actor and critic networks are updated at the same frequency. In contrast, TD3 updates the actor network less frequently than the critic networks. This allows the value estimates to stabilize before being used to update the policy, reducing variance in the learning process.

\subsection{Evaluation}
To evaluate the performance of the reinforcement learning agents, they are compared against the classical Black–Scholes delta-hedging strategy. A new set of simulated price paths is generated, which is not used during training. This ensures that the evaluation is conducted on unseen data, allowing us to assess the generalization ability of the learned policy rather than its ability to fit the training scenarios.
\\\\
Then four hedging strategies are considered. The first is the theoretical Black–Scholes delta, which serves as a benchmark. The other policies are learned by the different reinforcement learning agents: DQN, DDPG, and TD3. For each strategy, hedging is performed along the simulated price paths.
\\\\
Finally, the hedging costs are computed across a large number of simulated trials. These costs capture the total expense of maintaining the hedge in the presence of transaction costs and provide a basis for comparing the efficiency of the different approaches.

